  "so_what_questions": [
    "Why does Krishna rank practices in a descending hierarchy of accessibility rather than intrinsic worth — and what does that reveal about his pedagogy?",
    "Shankara and Madhusudana both read the praise of tyaga as a 'stuti' device (laudatory encouragement) rather than a literal ontological ranking — what are the stakes of that interpretive move?",
    "Ramanuja inserts the full bhakti-yoga sequence (karma → dhyana → jnana → para-bhakti) inside a verse that names only three terms — is this exegetically justified or a devotional overlay?",
    "Madhva's appeal to three distinct Vedic branch-citations (Anabhimlanasaka, Kashayani, Gopavana) to resolve the tension in the verse — what does this reveal about the Dvaita hermeneutical method?",
    "The verse promises shanti 'anantaram' (without interval) from tyaga — how do the schools differ on whether this means immediate liberation or merely the precondition for liberation?",
    "If the hierarchy runs abhyasa < jnana < dhyana < tyaga, why does the Gita elsewhere (3.7, 5.2) apparently rank karma-yoga above jnana-yoga — how do the commentators resolve this tension?",
    "Vallabha reads the hierarchy through the lens of Krishna's prasada (grace) rather than individual effort — how does this reshape the meaning of 'superior' (vishishyate) throughout the verse?"
  ],
  "everyday_applications": {
    "advaita": "When you are told to 'just practice' a skill daily without understanding why, notice that mechanical repetition without discernment (viveka) is the lowest rung; ask first what the practice is actually for, then commit to it — otherwise you are doing abhyasa without jnana.",
    "vishishtadvaita": "If you feel spiritually stuck in a technique you cannot sustain, do not abandon the path — step down to the rung you can actually hold. Uninspired practice is replaced by study; incomplete study by meditation; incomplete meditation by offering each day's work to Bhagavan without calculating the return. Each lower rung is a valid starting point, not a failure.",
    "dvaita": "Fruit-renunciation (karma-phala-tyaga) is not equivalent to doing nothing; Madhva insists it must be wedded to meditation on Hari to yield its result. In practice: do your work, release attachment to outcome, AND keep your mind anchored in remembrance of the Lord — neither half alone is sufficient.",
    "shuddhadvaita": "Vallabha's shanti is equanimity in gain and loss alike — what he calls svasthhya (inner wellness). The practical test: does your sense of okayness depend on whether the project succeeded today? If yes, phala-tyaga (fruit-renunciation) is still incomplete; work on it not by gritting your teeth but by returning every outcome to Krishna as his lila.",
    "bhakti": "Sridhara's emphasis on mat-prasada (the Lord's grace) as the proximate cause of shanti corrects a common misreading: the hierarchy is not about personal achievement climbing a ladder but about clearing channels through which grace can flow. Phala-tyaga clears the channel; grace then moves through it immediately.",
    "advaita-bhakti": "Madhusudana's 'Agastya-praise' analogy offers a reframe for motivational teachers: praising a student for small acts of generosity using the same language you would use for a saint is not flattery — it is a legitimately Shastraic device (stuti) that activates the quality already present in seed form. Use encouragement deliberately, knowing it works by partial-quality-sharing, not by false equivalence."
  }
}